06641nam a22011175i 9780691202211DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912022117 a10.1515/97806912022112doi  a(DE-B1597)544917  a(OCoLC)1165409493  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a305.89/43230512231 aRoberts, Sean R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe War on the Uyghurs :bChina's Internal Campaign against a Muslim Minority /cSean R. Roberts. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Muslim Politics ;v7800tFrontmatter -- tAbout the author -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Colonialism, 1759–2001 -- t2. How the Uyghurs became a ‘terrorist threat’ -- t3. Myths and realities of the alleged ‘terrorist threat’ associated with Uyghurs -- t4. Colonialism meets counterterrorism, 2002–2012 -- t5. The self-fulfilling prophecy and the ‘People’s War on Terror,’ 2013–2016 -- t6. Cultural genocide, 2017–2020 -- tConclusion -- tA note on methodology -- tTransliteration and place names -- tList of figures -- tList of abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow China is using the US-led war on terror to erase the cultural identity of its Muslim minority in the Xinjiang regionWithin weeks of the September 11 attacks on New York and Washington, the Chinese government warned that it faced a serious terrorist threat from its Uyghur ethnic minority, who are largely Muslim. In this explosive book, Sean Roberts reveals how China has been using the US-led global war on terror as international cover for its increasingly brutal suppression of the Uyghurs, and how the war's targeting of an undefined enemy has emboldened states around the globe to persecute ethnic minorities and severely repress domestic opposition in the name of combatting terrorism.Of the eleven million Uyghurs living in China today, more than one million are now being held in so-called reeducation camps, victims of what has become the largest program of mass detention and surveillance in the world. Roberts describes how the Chinese government successfully implicated the Uyghurs in the global terror war—despite a complete lack of evidence—and branded them as a dangerous terrorist threat with links to al-Qaeda. He argues that the reframing of Uyghur domestic dissent as international terrorism provided justification and inspiration for a systematic campaign to erase Uyghur identity, and that a nominal Uyghur militant threat only emerged after more than a decade of Chinese suppression in the name of counterterrorism—which has served to justify further state repression.A gripping and moving account of the humanitarian catastrophe that China does not want you to know about, The War on the Uyghurs draws on Roberts's own in-depth interviews with the Uyghurs, enabling their voices to be heard.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEthnic conflictszChinazXinjiang Uygur Zizhiqu. 0aMuslimsxRelationszChina. 0aPersecutionzChinazXinjiang Uygur Zizhiqu. 0aUighur (Turkic people)xCivil rightszChina. 0aUighur (Turkic people)zChinaxGovernment relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aBeijing.  aChina's Forgotten People.  aChinese Communism.  aChinese Communist Party.  aChinese internment camps.  aGardner Bovingdon.  aIslam.  aMaoism.  aMichael Clarke.  aNick Holdstock.  aStrangers in Their Own Land.  aTerrorism and Counter-Terrorism in China.  aWorld Trade Center attacks.  aXUAR.